description.narrative:
1. Agencies with policies and associated capacity to conduct biodiversity impact assessment of sectoral policies and plans; 
2. Programmes and policies to support biodiversity friendly agricultural production in critical landscapes; 
3. Systems and procedures for implementation of new regulations of trade in wild planst and animal resources; 
4. Policies to encourage investments in biodiversity friendly business; 
5. National biodiversity information system; 
6. LGUs with tools and capacities for mainstreaming biodiversity in local development policy making , planning, budgeting and M&E systems; 
7. LGUs with toolkits and implementation capacity fro applicatio of SEAs, as well as landscape level natural resource management, across multiple and individual LGUs; 
8. LGU development expenditures for identifiably BD friendly programmes and investments; 
9. LGUs in critical biogeographic regions with policy framework and technical capacity to support biodiversity friendly agricultural practices; 
10. LGUs in critical biogeographic regions with local regulations and capacity to implement policies on wildlife trade; 
11. LGUs with regulatory structures and incentive systems to encourage the development of biodiversity-friendly businesses, including investor codes of conduct; 
12. Mechanisms and capacities for intra LGU knowledge sharing on mainstreaming biodiversity; 
13. LGU development plans at project sites complying with SEA approach, as well as, landscape level natural resources management; 
14. Inter-LGU cooperation in planning and regulation of natural resource use; new conservation areas established; 
15. Farmers adopting BD friendly practices; 
16. Pressures from overharvesting of wild resources; 
17. Private investments in BD friendly business in selected project sites; communities receiving incentives fro shifting to sustainable practices; 
18. Data & KM systems to support local initiatives.
